05405nam a22007215i 9780773583375DE-B159720240306124542.0m|||||o||d||||||||cr || ||||||||240306t20152015xxc    fo  d z      eng d  a97807735833757 a10.1515/97807735833752doi  a(DE-B1597)656053  a(OCoLC)1394873109  aDE-B1597bengcDE-B1597erda0 aeng  axxccCA 4aK543.M8 ǂb H357 2015eb 7aSOC0490002bisacsh04a971.06481 aHalpern, Monda, eauthor.4aut4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/aut10aAlice in Shandehland :bScandal and Scorn in the Edelson/Horwitz Murder Case /cMonda Halpern. 1aMontreal ;aKingston ;aLondon ;aChicago : bMcGill-Queen's University Press, c[2015] 4c©2015  a1 online resource :b36 b&w photos  atextbtxt2rdacontent  acomputerbc2rdamedia  aonline resourcebcr2rdacarrier  atext filebPDF2rda0 aMcGill-Queen's Studies in Ethnic History ;v200tFront Matter -- tContents -- tAcknowledgments -- tIntroduction -- t“This terrible drama of humanity”: An Affair, a Shooting, a Death, an Arrest -- t“A prominent Ottawa jeweller” and “the jeweller’s comely young wife”: The Rise of the Edelsons -- t“Startling evidence … of a sensational character”: The Inquest, and Respectability Challenged -- t“Her life was pure impulse without control”: Trial by Jewry, Community Anxiety, and the Spurning of Alice -- t“In a court of British justice, sympathy has no place”: Trial by Jury, Respectability and Honour, and the Acquittal of Ben -- t“A sudden silence fell”: The Legacy of the Case -- tConclusion -- tA Note on Sources -- tNotes -- tBibliography -- tIndex0 arestricted accessuhttp://purl.org/coar/access_right/c_16ecfonline access with authorization2star  aBy 1931, Ben and Alice Edelson had been married for two decades and had seven children, but for years Alice had been having an affair with the married Jack Horwitz. On the night of 24 November, Ben, Alice, and Jack met at Edelson Jewellers to "settle the thing." Words flew, a brawl erupted, and Jack was shot and killed. The tragedy marked the start of a sensational legal case that captured Ottawa headlines, with the prominent jeweller facing the gallows. Through a detailed examination of newspaper coverage, interviews with family and community members, and evocative archival photographs, Monda Halpern's Alice in Shandehland reconstructs a long-silenced murder case in Depression-era Canada. Halpern contends that despite his crime, Ben Edelson was the object of far less contempt than his adulterous wife whose shandeh - Yiddish for shame or disgrace - seemed indefensible. While Alice endured the censure of both the Jewish community and the courtroom, Ben’s middle-class respectability and the betrayal he suffered earned him favoured standing and, ultimately, legal exoneration. Revealing the tensions around ethnicity, sexuality, gender, and class, Alice in Shandehland explores the divergent reputations of Ben and Alice Edelson within a growing but insular and tenuous Jewish community, and within a dominant culture that embraced male success and valour during the emasculating 1930s.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 06. Mrz 2024) 0aAdulteryxCase studiesxOntarioxOttawa. 0aAdulteryzOntariozOttawavCase studies. 0aAdultèrexÉtudes de casxOntarioxOttawa. 0aJewelersxCase studiesxOntarioxOttawa. 0aJewelerszOntariozOttawavCase studies. 0aJewsxCase studiesxOntarioxOttawa. 0aJewszOntariozOttawavCase studies. 0aJuifsxÉtudes de casxOntarioxOttawa. 0aProcès (Meurtre)xÉtudes de casxOntarioxOttawa. 0aScandales sexuelsxÉtudes de casxOntarioxOttawa. 0aSex scandalsxCase studiesxOntarioxOttawa. 0aSex scandalszOntariozOttawavCase studies. 0aTrials (Murder)xCase studiesxOntarioxOttawa. 0aTrials (Murder)zOntariozOttawavCase studies. 0aTriangle (Relations humaines)xÉtudes de casxOntarioxOttawa. 0aTriangles (Interpersonal relations)